Gamma-Poisson

Suppose we want to build a model that predicts the number of spam emails, \(Y\), that a given account receives in a given day. The Poisson distribution is a common discrete probability distribution to use for modeling the likelihood. This distribution has a single rate parameter \(\lambda\), which is the case can be thought of as the typical number of spam emails received in a day1. However, note that \(\lambda \in (0, \infty)\) and does not have to be a whole number. Our goal is to perform Bayesian inference on the Poisson rate parameter \(\lambda\).

  1. (2 points) Assuming e-mails arrive independently of one another, write down the poison likelihood up to a constant of proportionality. That is, express the likelihood function without including any constants that do not depend on \(\lambda\).

    \[ \begin{align} \mathcal{L}(\lambda) &= \prod_{i=1}^{n} \frac{e^{-\lambda} \lambda^{y_i}}{y_i!}\\ &= \frac{ e^{-n\lambda} \lambda^{\sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i}}{\prod_{i=1}^{n} y_i!}\\ &\propto e^{-n\lambda} \lambda^{\sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i} \end{align} \]

    Students may stop here, however, it is sometimes convenient to express \(\sum_{i=1}^n y_i\) as \(n \bar y\) instead. Hence:

    \[ \mathcal{L}(\lambda) \propto e^{-n\lambda} \lambda^{n \bar y} \]

  2. (2 points) A popular choice for prior distribution for \(\lambda\) is the Gamma distribution which has the following PDF:

    \[ f(x \mid \alpha, \beta) = \frac{\beta^\alpha x^{\alpha - 1} e^{-\beta x}}{\Gamma(\alpha)} \]

    where \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) are the positive shape and rate parameters, respectively. Express the Gamma prior up to a constant of proportionality.

    \[ \begin{align} p(\lambda) &= \frac{\beta^\alpha \lambda^{\alpha - 1} e^{-\beta \lambda}}{\Gamma(\alpha)}\\ &\propto \lambda^{\alpha - 1} e^{-\beta \lambda}\\ \end{align} \]

  3. (3 points) Show that the Gamma distribution is a conjugate prior to the Poisson likelihood. Identify (along with it’s parameters) the posterior distribution.

    \[ \begin{align} \text{posterior} &\propto \text{likelihood} \times \text{prior}\\ p(\lambda \mid y) &= e^{-n\lambda} \lambda^{n \bar y} \times \lambda^{\alpha - 1} e^{-\beta \lambda}\\ &= e^{-\lambda(\beta +n)} \lambda^{n \bar y + \alpha - 1} \\ &= e^{-\lambda \tilde \beta} \lambda^{\tilde \alpha - 1} \\ \end{align} \]

    which we can recognize as a gamma distribution with shape parameter \(\alpha' = \alpha + n \bar y\) and rate parameter \(\beta' = \beta + n\).

  4. (2 points) Now suppose we want to set the hyperparameters of our Gamma prior to match the prior belief that \(\lambda\) should reasonably lie between 0 to 8; that is, we expect an average of 0 to 8 spam emails on any given day. Use this information to develop a prior. Tips: there are interactive tools such as the distribution zoo that you may find helpful.

    Note there are no “right” or “wrong” answers here. Playing around with the applet, there may be a variety of answer. You can plug in the values at the distribution zoo to verify that the choice is reasonable given the directive. One example of a reasonable prior is given below:

    For a more systematic approach students may recall that for random variable \(X \sim \text{Gamma}(a,b)\) the mean is given by \(\mathbb{E}[X] = \frac{a}{b}\) and variance by \(\text{Var}(Y) = \frac{a}{b^2}\). Students may choose a value such that the mean is equal to 4 (the midpoint between the reasonable values of 0 and 8). In this case:

    \[ \begin{align} \mathbb{E}[X] &= \frac{a}{b} = 4\\ \implies a &= 4b \end{align} \]

  5. (2 points) Suppose we record the number of spam emails every day for a week a observe: {2, 0, 1, 3, 3, 5, 4}. What is the resulting posterior based on the prior you defined in the previous question? State the name of the posterior distribution and the values of it’s parameters for full marks.

    Supposing their hyperparameters for their prior are a and b, the resulting posterior would be of the form:

    \[ \begin{align} Y | \lambda \sim & \text{Gamma}(\texttt{a} + n \bar y, \texttt{b} + n)\\ & \text{Gamma}(3 + 7 \times 2.5714286, 1 + 7) & \text{(based on mine)}\\ & \text{Gamma}(21, 8) & \text{(based on mine)} \end{align} \]

When plotting these on the same graph, be sure to normalize each curve so that they are on the same scale. Also be sure to include a legend to differentiate them. Note: you may use functions from packages to help you with this (eg. from the bayesrules or LearnBayes packages), or plot it “from scratch” in R.

  7. (2 points) Did the data (i.e. likelihood) or your prior belief (i.e. prior) have equal influence on the resulting posterior or did one have more “strength” than the other. Justify your answer either mathematically or by either referencing the tri-plot.

    Since the posterior sits closer to the likelihood, the likelihood has more strenght. Mathematically we can see by comparing the likelihood to the prior:

    \[ \begin{align} \text{prior} &\propto e^{-\texttt{b} \lambda} \lambda^{\texttt{a} - 1} \\ \text{likelihood} &\propto e^{-n\lambda} \lambda^{\sum_{i=1}^{n} y_i} \end{align} \]

    that our prior rate b can be likened to the sample size \(n\) and the shape plus 1, a +1 , is comparable to the number of spam in b days. In my case, the prior I chose is akin to a belief in 4 spam emails in 1 days. Since b = 1 < \(n = 7\), the prior will have less strength on the resulting posterior.

  8. (1 point) Based on the resulting posterior, what would be the typical daily rate of spam emails? Hint: you may use properties and formula from the Gamma distribution Wikipedia page, or the ?summarize_beta_binomial() function from the bayesrules package to help you answer this.

    A point estimate can be presented in the form of the mean or mode of a Gamma. Pulling from Wikipedia, we know that a random variable \(X\sim\)Gamma(\(\alpha\), \(\beta\)) distribution has a mean and mode given by equations:

    \[ \begin{align} \text{mean} &= \mathbb{E}[X] = \frac{\alpha}{\beta} & \text{mode} &= \frac{\alpha-1}{\beta} \end{align} \]

    Assuming the posterior has the form \(\lambda \mid y \sim\) Gamma(\(\alpha'\) = a \(+ n\bar y\), \(\beta'\) = b + \(n\)), we can express the posterior mean as:

    \[ \begin{align} \mathbb{E}[\lambda \mid y] = \frac{\alpha'}{\beta'} = \frac{21}{8} = 2.625 \end{align} \]

    Notice how this value lies between the mean of our prior and the mean of our likelihood. Noting that our likelihood has the form \(y \mid \lambda \sim\) Gamma(\(\sum_i y_i\) + 1, \(n\)) (see Note 1 for explanation) the mean for likelihood curve can be expressed as:

    \[ \begin{align} \mathbb{E}[\lambda] &= \frac{\texttt{a}}{\texttt{b}} = \frac{3}{1} = 3\\ \end{align} \]

    Our likelihood mean value for \(\lambda\)

    \[ \begin{align} \mathbb{E}[Y | \lambda] & = \frac{\sum_i y_i + 1}{n} = 2.5714286 \end{align} \]

    An alternative estimate could be provided in the form of the mode. The posterior mode, more commonly referred to as the Maximum A Posteriori (MAP) estimate, represents the value of the parameter(s) of interest that maximizes the posterior distribution. Using the equations above (pulled from Wikipedia) our MAP estimate would be:

    \[ \hat \lambda_{MAP} = \frac{\texttt{a} + n\bar y - 1}{\texttt{b} +n} = \frac{3 + 7 \times 2.5714286- 1}{1 +7} = \frac{20}{8} = 2.5 \]

    Aside: notice how the mode of the likelihood (remeber the likelihood has the functional form of a Gamma(a+1, \(n\))) matches the MLE for a Poisson rate parameter. To put another way…

    The highest peak on the likelihood curve, is the mode of a Gamma(\(\sum_i y_i + 1, n\))) give by: \[ \frac{\sum_i y_i + 1 - 1}{n} = \frac{\sum_i y_i}{n} = 2.5714286 \] The MLE for the rate parameter of a Poisson distribution is give by: \[ \hat \lambda_{MLE} = \frac{\sum_i y_i}{n} = \frac{18}{7} = 2.5714286 \]

    Note that you could also obtain this information from the summarize_gamma_poisson() from the bayesrules package:

    summarize_gamma_poisson(
  shape = priora,   # shape of the Gamma prior
  rate = priorb,    # rate  of the Gamma prior
  sum_y = sum(y),   # sum of ovserved data values
  n = n)    
          model shape rate  mean mode      var       sd
1     prior     3    1 3.000  2.0 3.000000 1.732051
2 posterior    21    8 2.625  2.5 0.328125 0.572822
    Beta-Binomial

    Let \(Y\sim \text{Binomial}(n,\theta)\), where \(\theta\), the probability of success is our parameter of interest. Suppose we assume a beta prior for the probability of success, that is, \(p(\theta)\sim \text{Beta}(a, b)\). In class we showed that the beta distribution is a conjugate prior for \(\theta\).
